5c.title: Ontology Identification problem
5c.text:
We want an [advanced agent's](AdvancedAgents-1) goals to be over outcomes in the external environment - [we want the agent to want properties of the real world, not just want to experience particular sensory outcomes on a webcam].  It seems likely that for advanced agents, the agent's representation of the world will change significantly over time, in ways not foreseeable at compile time.  The ontology identification problem is to create a [preference framework](http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/5b) for the agent that is stable and optimizes particular external facts, even as the agent modifies its representation of the world in ways [we can't predict in advance](http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/5d).

# Difficulty

Suppose we want to build a [diamond maximizer](5g) that will turn as much of the physical universe into diamond as possible - a goal chosen to have a crisp-seeming definition for our universe: the amount of diamond is the number of carbon atoms covalently bound to four other carbon atoms (and a carbon atom is a nucleus with six protons, etcetera).  If we can crisply define exactly what a 'diamond' is, in theory it seems like we should be able to avoid issues of [Edge Instantiation](EdgeInstantiation-1), [Unforeseen Maximums](UnforeseenMaximums-1), and trying to convey [complex values] into the agent.

Even with this seemingly crisp and formalizable utility function, we might still confront two problems:

- We might not know the true, fundamental ontology of our own universe.
- We might not know how to count expected diamonds inside the agent's model of the world.

## True ontology of universe not known in development phase

Suppose that someone was trying to define a utility function about 'diamonds' in the era after the discovery of atoms, but before the discovery of nuclear physics or quantum mechanics.  They might try to define a utility function over universes composed of bound atoms, but [they would not know during the development phase](http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/devphase_unpredictable-1) how to define a utility function over universes composed of baryons or quantum fields.

Intuitively, we would *want* (as a design desideratum) for the agent to react to its discovery of nuclear physics by redefining the 'carbon atoms' that its old utility function cared about, as 'nuclei containing exactly six protons' in a new utility function that could evaluate the newly discovered, non-atomic, nuclear-physics universe.

This seems like the obvious thing that we want the agent to do, but we don't yet have a good general formalization of how you would rewrite the utility function when updating from an old model of the universe to a new model that no longer contains the objects of your utility function as primitive entities.  Is a carbon atom C-12, or can it contain any number of neutrons so long as there are six protons?  What sort of formula would answer this question automatically, rather than needing to appeal to human users?  And if a more complicated utility function says to ask the human users, who are the human users once you discover that those 'human' objects in the environment are actually just collections of quantum fields?
